Exercise 5.1.5 - PCA and Clustering

W. Mangrobang

August 27, 2018

Use what you learned in Section 4.3 and 4.4 to generate features from the mortality data using principal component analysis and clustering.

Remember that PCA and Clustering only apply to numeric variables, so unless you transform the categorical variables, you should only use the following four variables: issage, attage, duration, and exposure_face.

Use the techniques described above to generate additional features using the MEPS Data [RDATA1 (focus on a subset of your choice).

Optionally, use PCA or clustering to generate additional features using the numeric variables.

Save your file for future investigations.

The full MEPS dataset is quite large and generating additional features (especially if using binarization) will significantly increase the size and may cause memory issues. Make sure you select a subset of columns to work with for this exercise and remove the rest from your environment.

Mortality Data

PCA

We’ll perform PCA on the following four numeric variables: issage, attage, duration, exposure_face

## Importance of components:
##                           PC1    PC2    PC3       PC4
## Standard deviation     1.3474 1.1171 0.9679 1.465e-13
## Proportion of Variance 0.4538 0.3120 0.2342 0.000e+00
## Cumulative Proportion  0.4538 0.7658 1.0000 1.000e+00

100% of the variance is explained by the first three components. It kind of makes sense because attage is just a linear combination of issage and duration.

Let’s look at the loadings.

##                      PC1         PC2         PC3           PC4
## issage         0.6277823 -0.45739183  0.15830566 -6.096076e-01
## attage        -0.1686630 -0.86918081 -0.07748501  4.583378e-01
## duration      -0.7112405 -0.18484135 -0.20412148 -6.467651e-01
## exposure_face  0.2675427  0.03392794 -0.96294850  8.326673e-17

In a sense PC1 ~ issage, PC2 ~ attage, and PC3 ~ exposure_face.

I’ve seen a few rule of thumbs for PCAs.

  • Keep cumulative PCAs up to 80% of variance being explained. Here, this would be the first 3.
  • Elbow rule - similar to the one discussed in the materials for clustering, this one says keep PCAs below the elbow. Here this would be only PCA1.

Personally, I gravitate towards the first rule.

Let’s look at the loadings.

##                 PC1         PC2        PC3        PC4
## AGE14X   -0.6419825  0.03585475 -0.0816531  0.7615154
## TOTEXP14 -0.3483699 -0.70951943  0.5796247 -0.1981307
## WAGEP14X -0.3704330  0.70104369  0.5371661 -0.2876974
## FAMS1231  0.5738260  0.06192229  0.6073060  0.5459568

  • PC1 might be an indication that if a child is in the survey, then they are likely attached to a family; vice versa, a family of one
  • is likely an adult.
  • PC2 might show how that higher wage earners tend to have lower expenditures; a commentary on how higher income lets you afford services that increase your standard of healthy living.
  • PC3 might show how families will just have higher expenditures and wages.
  • PC4 might show how older adults likely have multiple children.

Interesting. I would say that the elbow is at 2 clusters. But I’m struggling for a straighforward interpretation. I think what the algorithm is seeing is that the that there’s more differentiation at the top end of family-sizes, which roughly coincides with the center point of age distribution. But it’s difficult to interpret, besides calling them ‘young’ vs ‘old’.
